{{other ships|USS Porter}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=[[Image:USS Porter DD-356.jpg|300px]] |Ship caption=USS Porter (DD-356) }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=United States |Ship flag={{USN flag|1942}} |Ship name= |Ship namesake= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=[[New York Shipbuilding Corporation]] |Ship laid down=18 December 1933 |Ship launched=12 December 1935 |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned=25 August 1936 |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship struck=2 November 1942 |Ship reinstated= |Ship honours= |Ship fate=*Sunk following enemy action, *26 October 1942 |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class={{Sclass|Porter|destroyer}} |Ship displacement=1,850&nbsp;tons |Ship length={{convert|381|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|36|ft|2|in|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draught= |Ship draft={{convert|10|ft|5|in|m|abbr=on}} |Ship propulsion=*50,000&nbsp;shp (37,285 kW); *Geared Turbines, *2 screws |Ship speed=35&nbsp;knots (65&nbsp;km/h) |Ship range=*6,500&nbsp;[[nautical mile|nmi.]] at 12&nbsp;knots *(12,000&nbsp;km at 22&nbsp;km/h) |Ship complement=194 |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament=*'''As Built:''' *1 × Mk33 Gun Fire Control System *8 × [[5"/38 caliber gun|5"(127mm)/38cal SP (4×2)]], *8 × 1.1"(28mm) AA (2x4), *8 × 21"(533mm) [[torpedo tube]]s (2x4) *'''c1942:''' *1 × Mk33 Gun Fire Control System *8 × [[5"/38 caliber gun|5"(127mm)/38cal SP guns (4×2)]], *2 X [[Bofors 40 mm gun|40mm AA]] (1x2), *6 × [[Oerlikon 20 mm cannon|20mm AA]] (6x1), *2 × Depth Charge stern racks |Ship armour= |Ship armor= |Ship aircraft= |Ship notes= }} |}
'''USS ''Porter'' (DD-356)''' was the [[lead ship]] in [[Porter class destroyer|her class]] of [[destroyer]]s in the [[United States Navy]]. She was the third Navy ship named for [[Commodore (United States)|Commodore]] [[David Porter (naval officer)|David Porter]] and his son, [[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[David Dixon Porter]].
==Operational history== ===Construction=== ''Porter'' was laid down by the [[New York Shipbuilding Corporation]] at [[Camden, New Jersey|Camden]] in [[New Jersey]] on 18 December 1933, launched on 12 December 1935 by Miss Carlile Patterson Porter and commissioned at [[Philadelphia]] on 27 August 1936, [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] Forrest B. Royal in command.
===1936-1941=== After shakedown in waters off [[Northern Europe]], ''Porter'' visited [[St. John's, Newfoundland]], for ceremonies in honor of the [[coronation of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth]] in May 1937 and was at the [[Washington Navy Yard]] during the Boy Scout Jamboree, June–July 1937.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} Then reassigned to the [[U.S. Pacific Fleet|Pacific Fleet]], she transited the [[Panama Canal]] and arrived at [[San Francisco, California]] 5 August 1937. She operated continuously with the Pacific Fleet until the outbreak of [[World War II]], homeported at [[San Diego, California]].
===World War II=== On 5 December 1941, ''Porter'' got underway from [[Pearl Harbor]], escaping the [[Japan]]ese [[attack on Pearl Harbor|attack]] by two days. She patrolled with [[cruiser]]s and destroyers in [[Hawaii]]an waters before steaming in convoy 25 March 1942 for the west coast.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} She operated off the west coast with Task Force 1 (TF&nbsp;1) for the next 4 months. Returning to Pearl Harbor in mid-August, she trained in Hawaiian waters until 16 October when she sortied with TF&nbsp;16 and headed for the [[Solomon Islands]].
====Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands==== On 26 October 1942, TF&nbsp;16 exchanged air attacks with strong Japanese forces northeast of [[Guadalcanal]] in the [[Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands]]. During the ensuing action, ''Porter'' was torpedoed, and, after the crew had abandoned ship, was sunk by gunfire from [[USS Shaw (DD-373)|''Shaw'']] (DD-373). Authorities differ as to the source of the torpedo which sunk ''Porter''. Author Eric Hammel states Porter was sunk by a single torpedo, part of a three-torpedo spread fired from Japanese [[submarine]] [[Japanese submarine I-21|''I-21'']].<ref>{{cite book|last=Hammel|first=Eric|title=Guadalcanal: The Carrier Battles|year=1987|publisher=Crown Publishers, Inc.|location=New York|pages=411–413}}</ref> However, author Richard B. Frank states that Japanese records don't support this, and that, more likely, an errant torpedo from a ditching US Navy [[Grumman TBF Avenger]] hit ''Porter'' and caused the fatal damage.<ref>{{cite book | last = Frank | first = Richard B. | authorlink = Richard B. Frank | year = 1990 | title = Guadalcanal : The Definitive Account of the Landmark Battle | publisher = [[Penguin Group]] | location = New York | isbn = 0-14-016561-4 }} p. 388-389.</ref> Her name was struck from the [[Naval Vessel Register|Navy List]] 2 November 1942.
''Porter'' earned one [[battle star]] for World War II service.
