The '''German destroyer Z1 ''Leberecht Maass''''' was a [[German World War II destroyers|Type 1934]] [[destroyer]] built for the ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' during the 1930s. The ship was named after [[Rear Admiral]] [[Leberecht Maass]] who commanded German forces in the [[Battle of Heligoland Bight (1914)|Battle of Heligoland Bight]] in August 1914.<ref name=ks7>Koop & Schmolke, p. 77</ref> Several days after the start of [[World War II]], she unsuccessfully attacked, together with another destroyer, Polish ships anchored at the naval base on the [[Hel Peninsula]]. ''Leberecht Maass'' was lightly damaged during the action. In mid-February 1940, while proceeding into the [[North Sea]] to search for British [[fishing trawler]]s, the ship was bombed by a patrolling German bomber that damaged her steering. She either drifted into a newly laid British [[minefield]] or was again hit by bombs and broke in half with the loss of the bulk of her crew.

==Design and description==
''Leberecht Maass'' had an [[length overall|overall length]] of {{convert|119|m|ftin|sp=us}} and was {{convert|114|m|ftin|sp=us}} [[Length at the waterline|long at the waterline]]. The ship had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|11.30|m|ftin|sp=us}}, and a maximum [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|4.23|m|ftin|sp=us}}. She displaced {{convert|2223|LT|t}} at [[Displacement (ship)#Standard displacement|standard load]] and {{convert|3156|LT|t}} at [[deep load]]. The two Wagner geared [[steam turbine]] sets, each driving one [[propeller shaft]], were designed to produce {{convert|70000|PS|kW shp|lk=on|abbr=on}} using steam provided by six high-pressure Wagner [[boiler]]s. The ship had a designed speed of {{convert|36|kn|link=on}}, but her maximum speed was {{convert|38.7|kn}}.<ref name=g9>Gröner, p. 199</ref> ''Leberecht Maass'' carried a maximum of {{convert|752|t|LT|0|sp=us}} of [[fuel oil]] which was intended to give a range of {{convert|4400|nmi|lk=in}} at a speed of {{convert|19|kn}}, but the ship proved top-heavy in service and 30% of the fuel had to be retained as [[Sailing ballast|ballast]] low in the ship.<ref>Whitley, p. 18</ref> The effective range proved to be only {{convert|1530|nmi|abbr=on}} at 19 knots.<ref>Koop & Schmolke, p. 26</ref>

The ship carried five [[12.7 cm SK C/34 naval gun|12.7 cm SK C/34 guns]] in single mounts with [[gun shield]]s, two each [[superfire|superimposed]], fore and aft. The fifth gun was carried on top of the aft [[superstructure]]. Her [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft]] armament consisted of four [[3.7 cm SK C/30]] guns in two twin mounts abreast the rear [[funnel (ship)|funnel]] and six [[2 cm FlaK 30/38/Flakvierling|2 cm C/30]] guns in single mounts. The ship carried eight above-water {{convert|53.3|cm|in|adj=on|sp=us}} [[torpedo tube]]s in two power-operated mounts. A pair of reload torpedoes were provided for each mount.<ref name=g9/><ref>Whitley, p. 68</ref> Four [[depth charge]] throwers were mounted on the sides of the rear deckhouse and they were supplemented by six racks for individual depth charges on the sides of the stern. Enough depth charges were carried for either two or four patterns of 16 charges each.<ref>Whitley, p. 215</ref> Mine rails could be fitted on the rear deck that had a maximum capacity of 60 [[naval mine|mine]]s.<ref name=g9/> A system of passive [[hydrophone]]s designated as 'GHG' (''[[Gruppenhorchgerät]]'') was fitted to detect [[submarine]]s.<ref>Whitley, pp. 71–72</ref> The crew numbered 10 officers and 315 enlisted men, plus an additional four officers and 19 enlisted men if serving as a [[flotilla]] [[flagship]].<ref name=g9/>

==Service history==
''Leberecht Maass'' was the first destroyer to be built in [[Germany]] since [[World War I]]. The ship was ordered on 7 July 1934 and [[Keel|laid down]] at [[Deutsche Werke]], [[Kiel]], on 10 October 1934 as yard number K232. She was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 18 August 1935 and completed on 14 January 1937.<ref>Whitley, p. 203</ref> She became the flagship of the ''Führer der Torpedoboote'' (Chief of Torpedo Boats) upon commissioning. ''Leberecht Maass'' spent most of her first year training and made a port visit to [[Gothenburg]] in April 1938. Upon her return she was taken in hand by Deutsche Werke to have her bow rebuilt to reduce the amount of water that came over the bow in [[head sea]]s. The ship participated in the August 1938 [[Fleet Review]] and the following fleet exercise.<ref>Whitley, pp. 79–80</ref> In December, ''Leberecht Maass'', together with her [[sister ship|sisters]] [[German destroyer Z2 Georg Thiele|Z2 ''Georg Thiele'']], [[German destroyer Z3 Max Schultz|Z3 ''Max Schultz'']], and [[German destroyer Z4 Richard Beitzen|Z4 ''Richard Beitzen'']], sailed to the area of [[Iceland]] to evaluate her seaworthiness in a [[North Atlantic]] winter with her new bow. On 23–24 March 1939, the ship was one of the destroyers that escorted [[Adolf Hitler]] aboard the [[pocket battleship]] {{ship|German cruiser|Deutschland||2}} to [[1939 German ultimatum to Lithuania|occupy Memel]].<ref name=ks7/> She participated in the Spring fleet exercise in the western Mediterranean, as the flagship of Rear Admiral [[Günther Lütjens]], and made several visits to Spanish and Moroccan ports in April and May.<ref>Whitley, p. 81</ref>

On 3 September 1939, Z1 ''Leberecht Maass'' and {{ship|German destroyer|Z9 Wolfgang Zenker||2}} took part in an attack on the Polish ships {{ship|ORP|Gryf||2}} and {{ship|ORP|Wicher|1928|2}} in [[Gdynia]] harbour. The Poles replied effectively and forced the German destroyers to make evasive maneuvers and to lay a [[smoke screen]] to throw off the aim of the Polish gunners. ''Leberecht Maass'' was hit in the superstructure by a {{convert|152|mm|sp=us|adj=on}} shell from the [[Coastal artillery|coast defense]] [[Artillery battery#Naval usage|battery]] at [[Hel, Poland|Hel]] that killed four crewmen and wounded another four men. Lütjens ordered the action broken off 40 minutes later as the German fire was ineffective. The following day, she sailed to [[Swinemünde]] to have her damage repaired, a process that took until 10 September. After its completion, ''Leberecht Maass'' helped to lay defensive minefields in the North Sea.<ref>Whitley, pp. 83–85</ref> The ship began a scheduled refit in Swinemünde on 29 September<ref name=ks8/> and Lutjens transferred his flag to {{ship|German destroyer|Z21 Wilhelm Heidkamp||2}}.<ref>Whitley, p. 85</ref> She was attached to the [[2nd Destroyer Flotilla (Germany)|2nd Destroyer Flotilla]] on 22 December.<ref name=ks8>Koop & Schmolke, p. 78</ref>

On 22 February 1940, ''Leberecht Maass'' and five other destroyers, Z3 ''Max Schultz'', Z4 ''Richard Beitzen'', {{ship|German destroyer|Z6 Theodor Riedel||2}}, {{ship|German destroyer|Z13 Erich Koellner||2}} and {{ship|German destroyer|Z16 Friedrich Eckoldt||2}}, sailed for the [[Dogger Bank]] to intercept British fishing vessels in "[[Operation Wikinger]]". En route, the flotilla was erroneously attacked by a [[Heinkel He 111]] bomber from ''[[Kampfgeschwader 26|KG 26]]''. ''Leberecht Maass'' was hit by at least one bomb, lost steering, and broke in half, sinking with the loss of 280 of her crew, among them the ship's commanding officer, ''[[Korvettenkapitän]]'' Fritz Bassenge. Only 60 men were saved. During the rescue effort, Z3 ''Max Schultz'' hit a mine and sank with the loss of her entire crew. Hitler ordered a [[Court of Inquiry (Naval)|Court of Inquiry]] to be convened to investigate the cause of the losses and it concluded that both ships that been sunk by bombs from the He 111. The Kriegsmarine had failed to notify its destroyers that the Luftwaffe was making anti-shipping patrols at that time and had also failed to inform the Luftwaffe that its destroyers would be at sea.<ref>Whitley, pp. 93–94</ref> Postwar evidence revealed that one or both ships struck a British minefield laid by the destroyers {{HMS|Ivanhoe|D16|2}} and {{HMS|Intrepid|D10|2}}.<ref>Rohwer, p. 15</ref>

