{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=[[Nazi Germany]] |Ship flag={{Shipboxflag|Nazi Germany|naval}} |Ship name=''U-557'' |Ship ordered=25 September 1939 |Ship builder=[[Blohm & Voss]], Hamburg |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number= |Ship way number= |Ship laid down=6 January 1940 |Ship launched=22 December 1940 |Ship commissioned=13 February 1941 |Ship homeport= |Ship identification= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship fate=Rammed and sunk by the Italian torpedo boat ''Orione'' west of Crete on 16 December 1941 |Ship notes= |Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class=[[German Type VII submarine#Type VIIC|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] |Ship displacement= *{{convert|769|t|LT|0}} surfaced *{{convert|871|t|LT|0|abbr=on}} submerged |Ship length= *{{convert|67.10|m|ftin|abbr=on}} [[o/a]] *{{convert|50.50|m|ftin|abbr=on}} [[pressure hull]] |Ship beam= *{{convert|6.20|m|ftin|abbr=on}} o/a *{{convert|4.70|m|ftin|abbr=on}} pressure hull |Ship height={{convert|9.60|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship draught={{convert|4.74|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship power= *{{convert|2800|–|3200|PS|kW bhp|abbr=on}} (diesels) *{{convert|750|PS|kW shp|abbr=on}} (electric) |Ship propulsion= *2 shafts *2 × [[diesel engine]]s *2 × [[Motor-generator|electric motors]] |Ship speed= *{{convert|17.7|kn|lk=in}} surfaced *{{convert|7.6|kn}} submerged |Ship range= *{{convert|8,500|nmi|abbr=on|lk=on}} at {{convert|10|kn}} surfaced *{{convert|80|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|4|kn}} submerged |Ship test depth= *{{convert|230|m|ft|abbr=on}} *[[Submarine depth ratings|Crush depth]]: {{convert|250|–|295|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship complement=4 officers, 40–56 enlisted |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament= *5 × {{convert|53.3|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s (four bow, one stern) *14 × [[torpedo]]es ''or'' 26 TMA mines *1 × [[8.8 cm SK C/35 naval gun|{{convert|8.8|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} deck gun]] (220 rounds) *various AA guns |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox service record |is_ship=yes |label= |partof=''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' |codes= |commanders=''[[Oblt.z.S.]]'' Ottokar Paulssen |operations= |victories= }} |}
'''''U-557''''' was a [[German Type VIIC submarine|Type VIIC]] [[U-boat]] built for [[Nazi Germany]]'s ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' for service during [[World War II]]. She was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 6 January 1940, [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 22 December 1940 and [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 13 February 1941. ''[[Oberleutnant zur See]]'' Ottokar Paulssen was in command throughout her career. For her first three war patrols her 2nd Watch Officer was [[Herbert Werner]], who later wrote the memoir of U-boat service, ''[[Iron Coffins]]''. She sank six merchant ships and one warship, a total of almost {{GRT|37000|disp=long}} over four patrols.<ref name="uboatnet" />
She was rammed and sunk by mistake by an Italian torpedo boat on 16 December 1941 west of [[Crete]].
==Design== [[German Type VII submarine#Type VIIC|German Type VIIC submarines]] were preceded by the shorter [[German Type VII submarine#Type VIIB|Type VIIB submarines]]. ''U-557'' had a displacement of {{convert|769|t|LT}} when at the surface and {{convert|871|t|LT}} while submerged.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}} She had a total length of {{convert|67.10|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a [[pressure hull]] length of {{convert|50.50|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|6.20|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a height of {{convert|9.60|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, and a [[draught (ship)|draught]] of {{convert|4.74|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. The submarine was powered by two [[Germaniawerft]] F46 four-stroke, six-cylinder [[supercharged]] [[diesel engine]]s producing a total of {{convert|2800 to 3200|PS|kW shp|-1}} for use while surfaced, two [[Brown, Boveri & Cie]] GG UB 720/8 [[Motor–generator|double-acting electric motors]] producing a total of {{convert|750|PS|kW shp}} for use while submerged. She had two shafts and two {{convert|1.23|m|ft|abbr=on|0}} [[propeller]]s. The boat was capable of operating at depths of up to {{convert|230|m}}.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}}
The submarine had a maximum surface speed of {{convert|17.7|kn}} and a maximum submerged speed of {{convert|7.6|kn}}.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}} When submerged, the boat could operate for {{convert|80|nmi}} at {{convert|4|kn}}; when surfaced, she could travel {{convert|8500|nmi}} at {{convert|10|kn}}. ''U-557'' was fitted with five {{convert|53.3|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s (four fitted at the bow and one at the stern), fourteen [[torpedo]]es, one [[8.8 cm SK C/35 naval gun|{{convert|8.8|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} SK C/35 naval gun]], 220 rounds, and an anti-aircraft gun. The boat had a [[Ship's company|complement]] of between forty-four and sixty.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}}
==Service history==
===Emergency in the Baltic=== ''U-557'' commissioned in February 1941, and was assigned to [[1st U-boat flotilla]], then based at [[Kiel]]. She spent the next four months at [[Königsberg]], working up in the [[Baltic Sea|Baltic]]. During this period she suffered a diving accident, during which one crewman died.<ref name=U557>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u557.htm |title=The Type VIIC Uboat U-557 |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> Werner describes this incident graphically in his book: He tells us that a routine dive in the [[Baltic Sea|Baltic]] turned into an emergency when the boat sank out of control. She hit the bottom stern-first with a thump. The depth gauge read {{convert|142|m|ft|abbr=on}}; the submarine was in severe difficulty, having taken on tons of water, poisonous chlorine gas was leaking from the batteries and there was the danger of an explosion. ''U-557'' had also suffered her first death; a mechanic sustained fatal head injuries in the after torpedo room. A human chain of sailors was formed, passing buckets of sea water to each other, in an attempt to shift some of the weight from the stern to the bow. After many hour's toil, the boat pivoted so that the bow hit the bottom. But the sheer weight of water (about 40 tons) prevented ''U-557'' from reaching the surface. The boat, having exhausted its supply of compressed air, stayed on the sea bed. The crew, under the direction of the Chief Engineer, rocked the boat by moving rapidly from stern to bow and back again. The submarine eventually worked herself free. After 20 hours, ''U-557'' surfaced and sailed on to Kiel.<ref>Werner pp. 16-19</ref>
===First patrol=== ''U-557'' departed from Kiel on 13 May 1941 to take up station in the Atlantic.<ref name=U557firstpatrol>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/patrols/patrol_1297.html |title=''U-557'' first patrol |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> On 24 May her captain was directed to support [[Operation Rheinübung|the sortie]] by battleship {{ship|German battleship|Bismarck||2}} and join a five boat patrol line west of the French coast to form a trap for units of the British [[Home Fleet]], which were in pursuit as ''Bismarck'' fled towards the French coast.<ref>Blair p288</ref>
Despite their efforts the trap failed and ''Bismarck'' was attacked and sunk on 27 May. The Home Fleet had been able to [[Last battle of the battleship Bismarck|track down and destroy ''Bismarck'']] without hindrance from the U-boat Arm.<ref>Blair pp. 289-292</ref>
The trap was dissolved and ''U-557'' was directed to join [[Wolfpack West|patrol line ''West'']], searching for North Atlantic convoys. However the ''Bismarck'' operation had disrupted U-boat operations and only two ships sunk in latter two weeks of May; one of these was ''Empire Storm'', sunk by ''U-557'' on 29 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/951.html |title=''Empire Storm'' |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref><ref>Blair p293</ref>
On 1 June ''U-557'' re-fuelled from supply ship ''Belchen'', but later that same day ''Belchen'' was caught and sunk by Royal Navy units [[Operation Rheinübung#Aftermath|engaged in hunting down]] the Operation ''Rheinübung'' supply train.<ref>Blair p299</ref>
On 3 June ''U-557'' joined Group ''West'', but the group had no success; this period following the [[Operation Primrose|capture of ''U-110'']] and the consequent [[Cryptanalysis of the Enigma|penetration of German Enigma code]] meant the [[Western Allies|Allies]] were able to re-route threatened convoys around areas of known U-boat activity and losses were kept to a minimum.<ref>Blair p305</ref>
''U 557'' abandoned her patrol after six relatively fruitless weeks, arriving at [[Lorient]] on 10 July.<ref name=U557firstpatrol/>
===Second patrol=== ''U-557'' sailed on her second war patrol on 13 August 1941, though she returned two days later (reason unknown), sailing again on 20 August to take position south of Iceland.<ref name=U557secondpatrol>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/patrols/patrol_1298.html |title=''U-557'' second patrol |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> On 24 August ''U-557'' found and reported [[convoy OS 4]] and commenced shadowing. As reinforcements arrived, Paulssen was permitted to attack; he made three approaches, sinking four ships in total.<ref>Blair p339</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/ops/convoys/convoys.php?convoy=OS-4 |title=OS 4 |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> Seven other U-boats joined the assault, but only one other had any success. ''U-557'' continued to shadow, but had no further success, and on 28 August the attack was called off. On 28 August ''U-557'' joined the [[Wolfpack Bosemuller|''Bosemuller'']] patrol line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/ops/wolfpacks/6.html |title=Group Bosemuller |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> On 2 September this was reconfigured into patrol line [[Wolfpack Seewolf|''Seewolf'']].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/ops/wolfpacks/8.html |title=Group ''Seewolf'' |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> Neither had any success and on 15 September ''U-557'' was ordered to return, arriving at Lorient on 19 September.<ref name=U557secondpatrol/>
===Third patrol=== On 19 November 1941 ''U-557'' sailed from Lorient bound for the [[Mediterranean]].<ref name=U557thirdpatrol>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/patrols/patrol_1300.html |title=''U-557'' third patrol |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> Werner had been reassigned and had left the boat at this point.<ref>Werner p68</ref> On 25/26 November she successfully penetrated the [[Straits of Gibraltar]], despite Allied [[Anti-submarine warfare|ASW]] patrols, and on 2 December sank the freighter ''Fjord'' off [[Estepona|Cape Estepona]], [[Spain]]. This caused some controversy, as a subsequent investigation showed this attack had infringed Spanish neutrality, taking took place within Spanish territorial waters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1210.html |title=''Fjord'' |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> ''U-557'' arrived at [[Messina]] on 7 December 1941.<ref name=U557thirdpatrol/>
===Fourth patrol=== On 9 December ''U-557'' sailed again on her fourth and last patrol, into the eastern Mediterranean.<ref name=U557fourthpatrol>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/patrols/patrol_1301.html |title=''U-557'' fourth patrol |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> In company with the {{ship|Italian submarine |Dagabur}}, on the night of 14/15 December 1941 she encountered the British light cruiser {{HMS|Galatea|71|6}}. Both submarines made attacks on the cruiser and she sank with the loss of more than half her crew.<ref>Blair p400</ref> ''U-557'' has been credited with the sinking.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1225.html |title=HMS ''Galatea'' |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref>
News of this sinking even reached the Submarine Tracking Room in London.<ref>Gannon, Michael - ''Operation Drumbeat - the dramatic true story of Germany's first U-boat attacks along the American coast in World War II'', 1990, Harper and Row publishers, ISBN 0-06-016155-8, p. 200.</ref>
==Fate== At 1806hrs on 16 December, ''U-557'' sent a short radio signal indicating that she was 18 hours from port. At 1800hrs on the same day, the Italian torpedo boat ''Orione'' left the Cretan port of [[Suda]]. The commander had no knowledge that a German U-boat was in the area of Crete.
When the Italian commander saw a submarine at 2144hrs, heading in a northerly direction, he decided to ram it, supposing it to be British. ''U-557'' sank immediately with all hands; the damaged Italian torpedo boat headed back to base. The position of the incident was given by the Italian commander as {{coord|35.31|N|23.19|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}.<ref name="uboatnet">{{Cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u557.html |title=The Type VIIC boat U-557 |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2014 }}</ref> <ref>Niestle p69</ref> An investigation by ''Supermarina'' (Italian Naval Command) determined the collision was an accident, though they reserved judgement on whether the ramming was intended, or the result of a navigational error.<ref>Kemp p75</ref> They also noted that German notification of ''U-557''{{'s}} presence in the area did not arrive with ''Supermarina'' until 2200hrs, after the incident had taken place.<ref name=U557/>
