{{Infobox event | image = [[File:Imber Village, Salisbury Plain 413.jpg|250px]] | caption = The houses at the training ground at Imber. | date = {{Start date|1942|04|13|df=yes}} | place = [[Imber]], [[Wiltshire]], [[United Kingdom]] | cause = Pilot error and bad weather | reported deaths = 25 | reported injuries = 71 }} The '''Imber [[friendly fire|friendly fire incident]]''' took place on the 13 April 1942 at [[Imber]], [[England]], during the [[Second World War]]. One of the [[Royal Air Force]] fighter aircraft taking part in a firepower demonstration accidentally opened fire on a crowd of spectators, killing 25 and wounding 71. Pilot error and bad weather were blamed for the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-wiltshire-17692313 |title=Memorial plaque for 25 WWII 'friendly fire' victims |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=2016-08-20}}</ref>
==Incident== [[Image:Hawker Sea Hurricanes.jpg|thumb|Six Hawker Hurricane similar to the aircraft involved]] On 13 April 1942 the weather was hazy and six Royal Air Force (RAF) [[Hawker Hurricane]]s from [[No. 175 Squadron RAF]] and six [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s from [[No. 234 Squadron RAF]] were being used for a demonstration of tactical airpower at [[Imber]], a [[British Army]] [[Salisbury Plain#Army Training Estate Salisbury Plain|training ground]] on [[Salisbury Plain]] in [[Wiltshire]]. The event was a dress rehearsal for an upcoming visit by [[Winston Churchill]] and General [[George Marshall]], [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<ref name="Lost">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7REOAQAAMAAJ|title=The Lost Villages: In Search of Britain's Vanished Communities|first=Henry|last=Buckton|year=2008|page=156|isbn=978-1-84511-671-2|publisher=I.B. Tauris}}</ref> and attended by a number of military personnel. The Spitfires overflew followed by the Hurricanes. Five of the Hurricanes hit the correct targets: several armoured vehicles and mock tanks. The pilot of the sixth Hurricane opened fire at the spectators before continuing with the demonstration. Casualties were {{nowrap|25 military}} personnel killed and {{nowrap|71 wounded.}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Memorial to be unveiled to personnel killed in Imber friendly fire incident |date=11 April 2012 |url= http://www.wiltshiretimes.co.uk/news/9641344.Memorial_to_be_unveiled_to_personnel_killed_in_Imber_friendly_fire_incident |last=Frampton |first=Will|website=Wiltshiretimes.co.uk|accessdate=2016-08-20}}</ref>
The following day the [[War Office]] and [[Air Ministry]] issued a joint statement: {{quote|During combined excercises to-day in Southern England there was an unfortunate accident in which a number of soldiers, including some members of the Home Guard, were killed and other injured. The next-of-kin have been informed.<ref name="times4">"News in Brief." ''Times'' [London, England] 14 April 1942: 4. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 21 September 2013.</ref>}}
First reports were that 14 had died with forty to fifty injured but this was later revised to 23 killed on the day (16 officers and seven soldiers). Four of the officers were members of the [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]].<ref name="times4" /><ref>"Combined Exercises Accident." ''Times'' [London, England] 15 Apr. 1942: 4. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 21 Sept. 2013.</ref> Two other officers died from wounds in the next few days, one on the 14 April the other (a Home Guard officer) on the 15 April to bring the total deaths to 25.
==Inquiry== The Court of Inquiry found the pilot, 21-year-old Sergeant William McLachlan was guilty of making an error of judgement and that the weather at the time contributed to the incident. The pilot of the Hurricane had misidentified the spectators as dummies, thinking that they were part of the demonstration when he opened fire.
An inquest held at Warminster into the 27 deaths{{#tag:ref|The Times report contradicts other sources that give the total deaths at 25.|group=N}} recorded that the deaths were caused by gunshot wounds and attributed to misadventure. The RAF pilot told the inquest he lost sight of the aeroplane he was following in the haze and realised he had made a mistake after he fired. The coroner also pointed out that, contrary to rumour, the pilot was British and not American.<ref>"News in Brief - Pilot who fired at Spectators." Times [London, England] 27 June 1942: 2. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 18 Sept. 2013.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Despite the statement from the coroner McLachlan was an American who had joined the Royal Canadian Air Force and officially a "Canadian"|group=N}}
==Aftermath== The demonstration for Churchill and Marshall went ahead as planned three days later.<ref name="Lost"/> McLachlan was killed when he was shot down in his Hurricane over [[France]] during a night raid on 29 June 1942.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/1079561/McLACHLAN,%20WILLIAM%20JOHN%20ANDREW |title=Casualty Details |website=Cwgc.org |date=1942-06-29 |accessdate=2016-08-20}}</ref> On the 13 April 2012, a plaque was unveiled on the 70th anniversary of the incident at St Giles' Church, [[Warminster]].<ref>{{cite web|author=1 |url=http://www.itv.com/news/west/2012-04-13/first-official-recognition-for-wartime-tragedy/ |title=First official recognition for wartime tragedy &#124; West Country |publisher=[[ITV News]] |date=2012-04-13 |accessdate=2016-08-20}}</ref>
